            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Henderson–Hasselbalch equation: definition</h2>
              <p>
                The Henderson–Hasselbalch equation is a convenient way to
                estimate the pH of a buffer solution from the acid dissociation
                constant and the ratio of conjugate base to acid. For a weak
                acid buffer:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pH = pK<sub>a</sub> + log<sub>10</sub> ( [A⁻] / [HA] )
                </p>
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>[HA]</strong> – concentration of the weak acid</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>[A⁻]</strong> – concentration of its conjugate base
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>pK<sub>a</sub></strong> – −log₁₀(K<sub>a</sub>) of the
                  acid
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For a weak base buffer, you can write an analogous expression in
                terms of pK<sub>b</sub> and the ratio base/conjugate acid, or
                convert to the conjugate acid’s pK<sub>a</sub>.
              </p>

              <h2>Forms of the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation</h2>

              <h3>1. Weak acid buffer (most common)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pH = pK<sub>a</sub> + log<sub>10</sub> ( [A⁻] / [HA] )
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is used for buffers like acetic acid/acetate,
                ammonium/ammonia (written in acid form), phosphate, etc.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Weak base buffer</h3>
              <p>
                You can express it in several equivalent ways. Two useful forms
                are:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pOH = pK<sub>b</sub> + log<sub>10</sub> ( [BH⁺] / [B] )
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono mt-2">pH = 14 − pOH</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                or, using the conjugate acid’s pK<sub>a</sub> (pK<sub>a</sub> +
                pK<sub>b</sub> = 14 at 25 °C):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pH = pK<sub>a, BH⁺</sub> + log<sub>10</sub> ( [B] / [BH⁺] )
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>
                3. Blood bicarbonate buffer (clinical Henderson–Hasselbalch)
              </h3>
              <p>
                In physiology, the equation is adapted to the bicarbonate–carbon
                dioxide buffer system in blood:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pH = 6.1 + log<sub>10</sub> ( [HCO₃⁻] / (0.03 × PCO₂) )
                </p>
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>[HCO₃⁻] in mEq/L (≈ mmol/L)</li>
                <li>PCO₂ in mmHg</li>
                <li>
                  0.03 is the solubility coefficient of CO₂ in blood
                  (mmol·L⁻¹·mmHg⁻¹)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Rearranging the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation</h2>

              <h3>1. Solve for base/acid ratio</h3>
              <p>Starting from the weak acid form:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pH = pK<sub>a</sub> + log<sub>10</sub> ( [A⁻] / [HA] )
                </p>
              </div>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Subtract pK<sub>a</sub> from both sides:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono">
                      pH − pK<sub>a</sub> = log<sub>10</sub> ( [A⁻] / [HA] )
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Raise 10 to the power of both sides:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono">
                      [A⁻] / [HA] = 10^(pH − pK<sub>a</sub>)
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>2. Solve for pK<sub>a</sub></h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pK<sub>a</sub> = pH − log<sub>10</sub> ( [A⁻] / [HA] )
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Solve for pH</h3>
              <p>This is already the standard form:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  pH = pK<sub>a</sub> + log<sub>10</sub> ( [A⁻] / [HA] )
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – pH of an acetate buffer</h3>
              <p>
                You prepare a buffer with 0.10 M acetic acid (HA) and 0.20 M
                sodium acetate (A⁻). The pK<sub>a</sub> of acetic acid is 4.76.
                What is the pH?
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Compute the ratio [A⁻]/[HA] = 0.20 / 0.10 = 2.0</li>
                <li>Take the logarithm: log₁₀(2.0) ≈ 0.301</li>
                <li>
                  Apply Henderson–Hasselbalch:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono">pH = 4.76 + 0.301 ≈ 5.06</p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Example 2 – Designing a buffer at a target pH</h3>
              <p>
                You want a buffer at pH 7.40 using a weak acid with pK<sub
                  >a</sub
                >
                = 7.20. What base/acid ratio is required?
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Use the rearranged equation:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono">
                      [A⁻]/[HA] = 10^(pH − pK<sub>a</sub>) = 10^(7.40 − 7.20) =
                      10^0.20 ≈ 1.58
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  This means you need about 1.6 times more conjugate base than
                  acid (in moles or concentration) to reach pH 7.40.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Example 3 – Blood pH from bicarbonate and PCO₂</h3>
              <p>
                A patient has [HCO₃⁻] = 18 mEq/L and PCO₂ = 30 mmHg. Estimate
                the arterial pH.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Compute the denominator: 0.03 × 30 = 0.9</li>
                <li>Compute the ratio: 18 / 0.9 = 20</li>
                <li>Take the logarithm: log₁₀(20) ≈ 1.301</li>
                <li>
                  Apply the equation:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono">pH = 6.1 + 1.301 ≈ 7.40</p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>When is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation valid?</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Buffer system:</strong> both acid and conjugate base
                  (or base and conjugate acid) are present.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>pH near pK<sub>a</sub>:</strong> typically within ±1
                  pH unit of pK<sub>a</sub>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Moderate concentrations:</strong> not extremely dilute
                  or extremely concentrated.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weak acids/bases:</strong> do not use it for strong
                  acids or bases alone.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Outside these conditions, you should solve the full equilibrium
                expression rather than relying on Henderson–Hasselbalch.
              </p>

              <h2>Common pitfalls and exam tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Do not use Henderson–Hasselbalch for a solution of a strong
                  acid with no conjugate base.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always use the <strong>ratio</strong> of base to acid;
                  absolute units cancel if they are consistent.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Remember that at pH = pK<sub>a</sub>, [A⁻] = [HA] (50%
                  protonated, 50% deprotonated).
                </li>
                <li>
                  For MCAT and similar exams, look for the presence of both acid
                  and conjugate base to justify using this equation.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">
                Frequently asked questions
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded">
                  <summary class="px-4 py-2 cursor-pointer font-medium">
                    What is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation used for?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="px-4 pb-3 pt-1 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    It is used to estimate the pH of buffer solutions and to
                    design buffers at a desired pH by choosing appropriate
                    ratios of weak acid and conjugate base (or weak base and
                    conjugate acid). In medicine, a modified form is used to
                    relate blood pH to bicarbonate and carbon dioxide levels.
                  </div>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded">
                  <summary class="px-4 py-2 cursor-pointer font-medium">
                    Can I use Henderson–Hasselbalch for strong acids and bases?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="px-4 pb-3 pt-1 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    No. The equation assumes a weak acid/base equilibrium and
                    the presence of both members of the conjugate pair. For
                    strong acids or bases without a buffer pair, you should
                    calculate pH directly from their concentration and
                    dissociation stoichiometry.
                  </div>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded">
